<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Energy and Climate Change Inquiry on Low Carbon Innovation</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">ubmitted by the Centre for Low Carbon Futures</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Centre for Low Carbon Futures (CLCF) is a collaborative membership organisation that focuses on sustainability for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">competitive advantage. Formed by the University of Birmingham, University of Hull, University of Leeds, University of Sheffield and University of York, we work across the EU, Asia and Latin America. The Centre brings together engineers, natural scientists </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and social scientists to deliver high-impact research on our 2013/14 themes of Energy Systems, Green Growth and Smart Infrastructure. We provide evidence to inform policy formation, encourage technological innovation and build capacity to improve resource </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">efficiency and promote sustainable leadership in the food-energy-water nexus. This has given us an insight on the process of low carbon innovation in the UK, and in a global context.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This response draws on the collective views of our members. CLCF contribu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ted to the National Audit Office report, and welcomes the opportunity to provide evidence to the Select Committee. We would be happy to elaborate before the Committee. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our key points are:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 67.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Support for energy innovation should reflect the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">systems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> nature of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the challenge. Current programmes are too focused on individual components, not their interaction.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Investment must come from public and private sectors. Industrial support for later stage innovation relies on stable policy from Government and greater trans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">parency of the decision-making process.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 66.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK should be making a stronger contribution to international energy innovation. The lack of a national lab is a barrier, but more should be done with existing bodies and mechanisms to project a coherent and coord</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inated response to global opportunities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Low Carbon Innovation and Coordination Group appears to be limited in its ability to provide the necessary leadership to drive forward development of the energy system and meet energy policy aims. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Responses t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">o questions</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Q1. Will the Government's current approach towards low carbon innovation help to achieve the UK's legally binding targets at the lowest possible cost?</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Successful low carbon innovation is likely to result from the co-evolution of technology, pol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">icies, business models, institutions and user practices.  Cost effective innovation is only likely to occur when the interplay between these is considered and current approaches tend to focus on just one of these, e.g. investment in technology or the Green</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Deal as a policy measure.   If the government was to take a more system oriented approach, the probability of a cost effective outcome would be greatly increased.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, it is important to stress that there is a major difference between an approach be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing cost effective and the most cost effective approach possible.  Making meaningful predictions on the latter </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through to 2050 is unlikely to be fruitful and transition pathway approaches (as promoted by DECC) recognise this at least implicitly.  The situa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion is similar to spreading one’s bets in investments.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our answer under Q5 relates to the need for public and private sector funding to work together as part of the more general approach.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Q2. Does the Government have the right balance of focus between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">energy efficiency, renewable energy and other low carbon technologies?</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The balance was reasonable in terms of policy, but delivery is more patchy and there are worrying signs of watering down a focus on energy efficiency.  There is widespread recognition t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hat supply side measures alone will not deliver on the 2050 carbon reduction targets and it is essential to also focus on demand.  It would be highly regrettable if an emphasis on energy efficiency were lost.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is also important to consider the order in w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hich activities need to occur.  E.g. in the short-term in particular, energy efficiency is highly cost effective.  Likewise, adding say a heat network first and only afterwards worrying about how efficiently this heat is used makes little sense.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Q3. What </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">outcomes, if any, are the LCICG likely to achieve? How should its forthcoming strategy drive more investment into low carbon innovation, and how should it measure success?</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would expect LCICG to act as a body which ensures support for innovation is coord</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inated across the funding agencies given their differing remits.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A research area in which CLCF is making a significant contribution is energy storage. We have seen multiple calls from different organisations (DECC, TSB, EPSRC, ETI) be launched over the las</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t year without any apparent connectivity between them. This follows a report from the Energy Research Partnership in June 2011</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which recommended that funders set out a coherent strategy for the analysis and development of energy storage technologies, alon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gside development of a strategic roadmap. A report from CLCF in March 2012</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> also called for a long-term vision for storage that is consistent with developments in the wider energy system which would be best delivered by a roadmap. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In terms of skills, know</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ledge and innovation, LCICG appears to have good potential for success, but how this has been translated into delivery is less clear.  It is unclear whether the LCICG has sufficient “clout” within government to deliver on its potential. To deliver an effec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tive strategy for low carbon innovation across multiple organisations requires both leadership and resource, neither of which appear to be available. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In terms of measuring success, it is rather hard to know how to deconvolute</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the specific success of LCICG from successful carbon reduction overall. A simplistic target-driven approach risks focusing on the short-term outputs rather than long-term outcomes.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Q4. Are the Government &amp; LCICG targeting investment towards the most effe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ctive stages of the innovation process, including over the long-term?</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The overall energy landscape in the UK is both complicated and convoluted and so it is hard to generalise in a meaningful fashion either as an objective observer or perhaps still less as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a participant unable to see a clear overall picture.  E.g. practice the LCICG has limited control over what government as a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whole does and government does no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t control the whole of energy investment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The essence of this is a decision on whether it is bette</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r in terms of overall outcomes to invest in the easy parts (high probability of success) or the difficult parts (high impact, but hard to do).  Approaches by both government and industry seem to be a mixture of these and there is no obvious consistency of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">either goals or methods.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Q5. What is the impact of the short-term funding timelines on private sector investment?</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Short-term funding timelines (especially for early stage innovation) can be a consequence of too strong a link between innovation priorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and energy policy. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A fear within the renewables and low-carbon sectors is that much of the potential advantage and innovation in technology may stall or indeed be lost due to the lack of available investment. Investment on the scale that is needed to achi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eve the legally binding low-carbon targets, is significant and unlikely to come from one source. The funds need to be raised from a range of sources, including government and private investors. The ability to raise this level of investment is reliant on th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e stability of the market and the perceived risks associated with both the individual technology and the industry as a whole. It has been evident that the levels of investment needed to develop the renewables and low-carbon sectors have not yet been fully </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">realised.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Much rhetoric has been heard why this is so but there is relatively little evidence. Common sense says that if the renewables and low-carbon sectors do not have long term stability (through secure, long term government policy) it will be difficul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t to raise the required finance. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One study that has researched this and used primary interviews is ‘An exploratory investigation of barriers and enablers affecting investment in renewable companies and technologies in the UK’</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.This investigation explores </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the perceived barriers and enablers to renewable technologies within the investment and renewables. 14 in-depth interviews with representatives from renewable energy producers, banks and investment companies identified key factors affecting the psychology </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of investor behaviour in renewables. Eight key issues are highlighted, including a range of barriers and enablers, the role of the government, balance between cost/risk, value/return on investment, investment time scales, personality/individual differences</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of investors and the level of innovation in the renewable technology. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Significantly, the role of the government was discussed more than other themes and generally in quite critical terms, highlighting the need to ensure consistency in government funding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and policy and a greater understanding of how government decision making happens.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Q6. How should DECC ensure that its remaining capital allocation for low carbon innovation will be spent wisely, after two years of underspend?</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A problem with this programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is that it only pays for capital and without running cost support investments can sit idle.  A life cycle funding approach would make a significant difference.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Q7. How is the Government maximising opportunities to learn from and partner with internationa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">l partners within and beyond the EU?</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Without a national energy lab in the UK, we do not have a single clear voice internationally, in the way that other countries within Europe and beyond do. Our experience is that UK representation is often piecemeal and ad hoc, although each interaction may</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be of high quality. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The range of actors which are active internationally include Government departments (often multiple, including DECC, DfT, Defra, BIS, FCO), funding agencies, universities (with many acting individually), consortia of universities (suc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h as our own, but others exist), learned societies, companies and trade bodies. Each of these will have their own priorities in terms of technology and outcomes. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Energy Research Centre (UKERC), as a quasi-national lab, has taken an effective leader</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ship position for the research community, which at least ensure the UK is represented alongside other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">countries. However, it is not resourced to engage across the sector at the level required, nor can it direct research effort as other national labs can. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The LCICG would seem to be the natural place for at least public bodies to agree a set of national priorities, which could be presented internationally, and help target the UK’s involvement in collaborative working. This is lacking at present. For example,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> we have found that many HMG representatives working in British embassies overseas do not recognise the position of energy storage as one of the Government’s ‘Eight Great Technologies’. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">The future role for energy storage in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">’, Energy Research Partnership (2011); available at </span><a href="http://www.energyresearchpartnership.org.uk/energystorage"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.energyresearchpartnership.org.uk/energystorage</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">‘Pathways for energy storage in the UK’, Centre for Low Carbon Futures (2012); available at </span><a href="http://www.lowcarbonfutures.org/energy-storage"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.lowcarbonfutures.org/energy-storage</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Wells V, Greenwell F, Covey J, Rosenthal HES, Adcock M, Gregory-Smith D. (2013) ‘An exploratory investigation of barriers and enablers affecting investment in renewable co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">mpanies and technologies in the UK’. Interface Focus 3:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">20120039. </span><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1098/rsfs.2012.0039"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://dx.doi.org/10.1098/rsfs.2012.0039</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>